{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619097"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16530"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16530"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.14,0.55,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9221"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"2092"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7202"},{"type":"tags","id":"8509"},{"type":"tags","id":"8851"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset right-sided weakness. His medical history includes hypertension and atrial fibrillation, for which he takes amlodipine and warfarin. On examination, his vital signs are stable. Neurological examination shows right-sided hemiparesis, right-sided lower facial weakness, and deviation of the tongue to the right on protrusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerve motor nuclei receives unilateral rather than bilateral corticobulbar innervation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trigeminal nerve motor nucleus","Abducens nerve nucleus","Glossopharyngeal nerve motor nucleus","Hypoglossal nerve nucleus","Vagus nerve motor nucleus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E receives only unilateral innervation from the contralateral motor cortex via the corticobulbar tract. This explains why a unilateral upper motor neuron lesion causes the tongue to deviate toward the weak side when protruded, as seen in this patient with likely stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options all receive bilateral innervation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve motor nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E receives bilateral innervation, protecting against unilateral weakness of jaw muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabducens nerve nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E has bilateral input, preventing isolated lateral rectus weakness from unilateral lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve motor nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E receives bilateral innervation, maintaining swallowing function even with unilateral lesions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve motor nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E also has bilateral input, preserving palatal and laryngeal function in unilateral strokes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lower motor nucleus of the facial nerve is another exception, receiving only contralateral corticobulbar input. This explains the characteristic pattern of central facial weakness affecting only the lower face in stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The hypoglossal nucleus receives unilateral corticobulbar innervation from the contralateral motor cortex.","Most cranial nerve motor nuclei receive bilateral corticobulbar innervation, protecting against unilateral upper motor neuron lesions.","Understanding corticobulbar innervation patterns explains clinical findings like tongue deviation in stroke."],"references":["W\u0119giel A, Zielinska N, G\u0142owacka M, Olewnik \u0141. Hypoglossal Nerve Neuropathies-Analysis of Causes and Anatomical Background. Biomedicines. 2024 Apr 14;12(4):864. doi: 10.3390/biomedicines12040864. PMID: 38672218; PMCID: PMC11048189.","Emos MC, Agarwal S. Neuroanatomy, Upper Motor Neuron Lesion. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725990Kim SY, Naqvi IA. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 12 (Hypoglossal). 2022 Nov 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30422464.","Netter, F. H. (2015).\u00a0Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16530"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:32:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T22:24:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9221"}},